<article>
    <h1>MATILDA HOUSE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200823/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-23"><time>2020-08-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FEATURES</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>In 1902, Joseph Cashin, a descen­dant of one of Sin­ga­pore’s old­est Ir­ish fam­i­lies, built a red-tiled bun­ga­low for his wife.</p>
    <p>The six-bed­room, sin­gle-storey house in Pung­gol Cen­tral, flanked by lush fruit or­chards, was named Matilda House, in mem­ory of Mr Cashin’s beloved mother, and be­came the fam­ily’s week­end re­sort.</p>
    <p>The house was ac­quired by the Gov­ern­ment in the mid-1980s and gazetted for con­ser­va­tion by the Ur­ban Re­de­vel­op­ment Author­ity in 2000 after it was mys­te­ri­ously aban­doned for two decades and fell into dis­re­pair.</p>
    <p>You get the pic­ture: Ru­ins means there must be a ghost story some­where.</p>
    <p>Peo­ple started spread­ing ru­mours that it was a guiwu (ghost house in Man­darin) and called it Is­tana Menanti, or “the palace where one waits” in Malay.</p>
    <p>And – you guessed it – res­i­dents in the area soon spot­ted the oblig­a­tory “woman with long hair”.</p>
    <p>In 2015, it was con­verted into a club­house for the res­i­dents of A Trea­sure Trove con­do­minium – and no one is com­plain­ing now.</p>

